âœ… Step-by-Step Guide to Create VPC for OpenSearch + Lambda
ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Create a VPC
Go to VPC Console â†’ Create VPC

Choose "VPC and more"

Set:

Name: my-vpc-opensearch

CIDR Block: 10.0.0.0/16

Tenancy: Default

Click Create VPC

ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Create 2 Public and 2 Private Subnets (in different AZs)
Type	Subnet Name	AZ	CIDR Block
Public	public-subnet-a	ap-south-1a	10.0.0.0/24
Public	public-subnet-b	ap-south-1b	10.0.1.0/24
Private	private-subnet-a	ap-south-1a	10.0.2.0/24
Private	private-subnet-b	ap-south-1b	10.0.3.0/24

ğŸ”¹ Step 3: Create an Internet Gateway
Go to Internet Gateways â†’ Create

Name: my-vpc-igw

Attach it to the VPC my-vpc-opensearch

ğŸ”¹ Step 4: Create a NAT Gateway (for Lambda's internet access)
Go to Elastic IPs â†’ Allocate new address

Go to NAT Gateways â†’ Create NAT Gateway

Name: my-vpc-nat

Subnet: Choose one of the public subnets

Elastic IP: Choose the one allocated above

Create and wait until Available

ğŸ”¹ Step 5: Create Route Tables
5a. Public Route Table (for public subnets)
Add Route:

Destination: 0.0.0.0/0

Target: Internet Gateway

Attach to:

public-subnet-a

public-subnet-b

5b. Private Route Table (for Lambda and OpenSearch)
Add Route:

Destination: 0.0.0.0/0

Target: NAT Gateway

Attach to:

private-subnet-a

private-subnet-b

ğŸ”¹ Step 6: Create OpenSearch Domain inside VPC
Go to OpenSearch â†’ Create Domain

Select:

Deployment type: Production

Network: VPC

VPC: my-vpc-opensearch

Subnets: private-subnet-a, private-subnet-b

Security group: Create one or use existing allowing port 443 inbound from Lambda SG

Configure access policy using IAM or fine-grained roles

ğŸ”¹ Step 7: Create Lambda with VPC Access
Go to Lambda Console â†’ Create function

Choose:

VPC: my-vpc-opensearch

Subnets: private-subnet-a, private-subnet-b

Security group: Allow outbound to OpenSearch SG (port 443)

